Rectosigmoid cancer.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Burns is a delightful 75-year-old gentleman who presents for further treatment of rectosigmoid cancer.  He has had hematochezia intermittently for years and has had treatment for hemorrhoids.  However, lately he has noticed more of a change in his bowel habits and an increase in bloating.  He underwent colonoscopy December 18, 2009, which demonstrated a mass in the rectosigmoid junction described as 16 cm from the anus.  Biopsies taken from the mass were positive for invasive adenocarcinoma.  Lakeview Family Practice Pathology has received slides and interpretation is pending.  Internal and external hemorrhoids were likewise noted.  No synchronous lesions were observed.  Staging CT abdomen and pelvis and chest x-ray were negative for metastatic disease.  No worrisome incidental findings were noted.  Laboratory studies indicate a normal hemoglobin at 14.4.  His PSA is normal at 2.8, CEA is normal at 1.5 ng/mL in this nonsmoking gentleman.  Mr. Burns presents for surgical treatment.
Mr. Burns is otherwise healthy.  Chronic comorbidities include hypertension for which he uses lisinopril.  He has no other cardiopulmonary history.  There is no history of bleeding disorders, anesthesia reactions, medications, allergies, sleep apnea, diabetes, heart attack, stroke, or glaucoma.

[end section id="20103"]

